ere we pair each `k` with `4n - 1 - k`. The sum of each pair is `(k + 1) + (4n - k) = 4n + 1`. \n\nIn particular, if `S` contains exactly one element from each such pair, then the sum of `S` will be `n * (4n + 1)/2`, but we need it to be `n * (4n + 1)`. \n\nHmm, no: there are `4n` elements, so `2n` pairs, and sum of `(k + 1)` for all elements is `(4n)(4n + 1)/2 = n(4n + 1)`, so if we take `S` to be `n` pairs, it will have sum `n(4n + 1)/2`, which is half the total sum, so the sum of `S` and `Sᶜ` would be equal. \n\nBut the coloring condition might not be compatible with this pairing. We have to take exactly two elements per color.\n\nBut perhaps we can do both things at once: for each color class, choose two elements that are paired with two other elements in such a way that we get one per pair globally. \n\nThis is complicated, but perhaps we should try to think differently.\n\nActually, perhaps we can find `S` such that for each color class, `S` contains exactly two of its elements, and in addition, `S` is a union of pairs of the form `{k, 4n - 1 - k}`. \n\nBut this is not always possible, as some pairs `{k, 4n - 1 - k}` might have both elements of the same color, and if we must pick exactly two of that color, we cannot avoid also having the pair in `S`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can find `S` as follows:\n1. For each color class `i`, take two elements of that class whose indices `(k + 1)` sum to the same value for all color classes. \n\nBut no, because the indices for different colors could look very different.\n\nWait, perhaps there is a better invariant. \n\nHere’s an observation:\nThe sum condition is equivalent to `2 * sum_{i ∈ S} (i + 1) = 4n(4n + 1)/2`, i.e., `sum_{i ∈ S} (i + 1) = n(4n + 1)`.\n\nBut perhaps we are overthinking it. Perhaps instead, notice that in the case of `n=1`, the only way is to have `S` be 2 elements, whose sum of `(i + 1)` is `(0 + 1) + (1 + 1) = 3`, which is the same as `(2 + 1) + (3 + 1) = 6`, no, wait:\n\nWait, `n=1`: `4 * n = 4`, `Fin (4 * n) = {0, 1, 2, 3}`. The sum of `(k + 1)` is `1 + 2 + 3 + 4 = 10`. So `S` must have sum `5`. The possible subsets of size 2 are {0,3} (sum `1 + 4 = 5`), {1,2} (sum `2 + 3 = 5`). So in this case we can choose either one. \n\nHere, for each color, `i : Fin 1`, `i = 0`, there are 4 elements colored `i=0`. But the hypothesis says that `c : Fin 4 → Fin 1`, and `∀ i : Fin 1`, the number of `j` such that `c j = i` is 4. So `c` is the constant function `0`. \n\nTherefore, `S` must contain exactly two elements. We can choose `S = {0, 3}`, which has `|{j ∈ S | c j = 0}| = 2`.\n\nSimilarly for `S = {1,2}`. \n\nNow, for `n=2`, `4 * n = 8`, and each `i : Fin 2` has exactly 4 preimages. The sum is `1 + 2 + ... + 9 = 36`, so `S` must have sum `18`. \n\nThis seems a bit involved, but perhaps we can try the following:\nFor each color class, pick the two smallest or two largest elements in that class, and verify that the sum works out.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps it’s better to realize that there are `n` color classes, each of size 4, and we need to pick two per class. The total sum is `n(4n + 1)`, and perhaps we can find such an `S` by averaging: if we pick two random elements from each color class, the expected sum of their `(i + 1)` will be 2/4 of the sum of `(i + 1)` for each color class. \n\nBut perhaps instead we should use the fact that for each color class `{a,b,c,d}`, there are at least two pairs of elements whose sums are equal. No, as earlier, this isn’t true if they’re `{1, 2, 3, 6}`.\n\nBut in that case, pairs are `1+2=3`, `1+3=4`, `1+6=7`, `2+3=5`, `2+6=8`, `3+6=9`. Hmm. Actually, if we take two pairs from different colors, can we adjust them?\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can make a general construction where, for each color class, we take the two smallest or two largest elements. \n\nBut perhaps a better approach is the following: instead of trying to force a particular `S`, we can use linear algebra. Since we have `4n` elements and we’re choosing `S` of size `2n`, with `n` constraints (for each color class, we want exactly two elements in `S`), perhaps there is always a solution. \n\nHowever, for Lean, perhaps we need a concrete construction. \n\nAnother idea: partition each color class into two pairs, and try to pick one pair per color class to include in `S`. But the sum of `S` would then depend on the pairs we choose, and we need to make sure it is exactly half the total sum.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps instead of constructing `S` explicitly, we can show that some averaging process works.\n\nBut perhaps all of these ideas are too complicated. \n\nHere's another observation: the condition is symmetric in the sense that we could take the complement of `S`, so perhaps we can try to find a random subset and then adjust it. \n\nBut perhaps instead we can use the probabilistic method to argue that some subset exists, but Lean wants a concrete proof.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps there is a way to use the fact that the average sum per color is fixed. \n\nUpon reflection, perhaps the following works:\n\nFor each color class `i`, we have 4 elements, say `x_{i1}, x_{i2}, x_{i3}, x_{i4}`. Since the sum of these four is `A_i`, if we choose two of them, their sum can range from the sum of the smallest two to the sum of the largest two. \n\nIf we sum over all colors, the sum of all `A_i` is `n(4n + 1)`, so if we take two elements from each color, the sum of their sums should be `n(4n + 1)/2`. Wait no: to get the sum of `S` to be half the total sum, we need the sum of picks to be half of `n(4n + 1)`, but the sum of all `A_i` is `n(4n + 1)` because `∑_{k=0}^{4n - 1} (k + 1) = (4n)(4n + 1)/2 = 2n(4n + 1)` and our desired sum is `n(4n + 1)`. But this doesn't seem directly helpful. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we should just try to prove that we can find a sum in each color class that works out. \n\nBut perhaps a better approach is to realize that we can actually pick `S` to be the union of two color classes! \n\nWait, no: because `S` is required to have exactly two elements of each color, not two entire color classes. \n\nWait no: the hypothesis is that for each `i : Fin n`, there are 4 `j` with `c j = i`, but the codomain of `c` is `Fin n`, so `i` ranges from `0` to `n - 1`, and for each `i` there are 4 preimages. \n\nSuppose instead that we take `S` to be the first two elements of each color class (with respect to some ordering). But the ordering is arbitrary. \n\nAlternatively, since the coloring is arbitrary, perhaps no concrete construction works",
      "\n  have h₁ : n = 0 := by\n    by_contra hn\n    -- Assume n ≠ 0 and derive a contradiction\n    have hn' : n ≠ 0 := hn\n    have h₂ : 0 < n := Nat.pos_of_ne_zero hn'\n    -- For each i : Fin n, we have #{j | c j = i} = 4\n    have h₃ : ∀ (i : Fin n), (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin (4 * n))).card = 4 * n := by\n      intro i\n      simp [Finset.card_univ]\n    have h₄ : ∀ (i : Fin n), (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin (4 * n))).card = 4 * n := by\n      intro i\n      simp [Finset.card_univ]\n    -- Count the total number of pairs (j, i) such that c j = i\n    have h₅ : ∑ i : Fin n, (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) = 4 * n := by\n      calc\n        ∑ i : Fin n, (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin n, 4 := by\n          -- For each i, the number of j's is 4\n          congr\n          ext i\n          rw [show (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) = 4 by simpa using h i]\n        _ = ∑ i : Fin n, 4 := rfl\n        _ = 4 * n := by\n          simp [mul_comm]\n          <;> simp [Finset.sum_const, Finset.card_fin]\n          <;> ring\n          <;> simp_all [mul_comm]\n    -- The sum of the cardinalities should equal the total number of elements in Fin (4 * n)\n    have h₆ : ∑ i : Fin n, (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), 1 := by\n      calc\n        ∑ i : Fin n, (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin n, (Finset.card {j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) := by simp [Nat.cast_id]\n        _ = ∑ i : Fin n, (Finset.card (Finset.filter (fun j => c j = i) (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin (4 * n)))) : ℕ) := by\n          congr\n          ext i\n          simp [Finset.filter_eq']\n        _ = ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), 1 := by\n          -- Use the fact that each j is counted exactly once in the sum over i\n          calc\n            ∑ i : Fin n, (Finset.card (Finset.filter (fun j => c j = i) (Finset.univ : Finset (Fin (4 * n)))) : ℕ) =\n                ∑ i : Fin n, ∑ j in Finset.univ, if c j = i then 1 else 0 := by\n              congr\n              ext i\n              simp [Finset.sum_ite, Finset.filter_eq']\n              <;> simp [Finset.card_univ]\n            _ = ∑ j in Finset.univ, ∑ i : Fin n, if c j = i then 1 else 0 := by\n              rw [Finset.sum_comm]\n            _ = ∑ j in Finset.univ, 1 := by\n              apply Finset.sum_congr rfl\n              intro j _\n              have h₇ : ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = 1 := by\n                have h₈ : ∃! (i : Fin n), c j = i := by\n                  refine' ⟨c j, _⟩\n                  constructor\n                  · rfl\n                  · intro i hi\n                    simp_all\n                obtain ⟨i, hi, hu⟩ := h₈\n                calc\n                  ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin n, if c j = i then 1 else 0 := rfl\n                  _ = 1 := by\n                    calc\n                      ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin n, if c j = i then 1 else 0 := rfl\n                      _ = 1 := by\n                        have h₉ : ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = 1 := by\n                          calc\n                            ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin n, if c j = i then 1 else 0 := rfl\n                            _ = 1 := by\n                              -- Only one term in the sum is 1, the rest are 0\n                              have h₁₀ : ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = 1 := by\n                                calc\n                                  ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin n, if c j = i then 1 else 0 := rfl\n                                  _ = 1 := by\n                                    -- Use the fact that there is exactly one i such that c j = i\n                                    have h₁₁ : ∃! (i : Fin n), c j = i := by\n                                      refine' ⟨c j, _⟩\n                                      constructor\n                                      · rfl\n                                      · intro i hi\n                                        simp_all\n                                    obtain ⟨i, hi, hu⟩ := h₁₁\n                                    calc\n                                      ∑ i : Fin n, (if c j = i then 1 else 0 : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin n, if c j = i then 1 else 0 := rfl\n                                      _ = 1 := by\n                                        -- Only one term in the sum is 1, the rest are 0\n                                        simp_all [Finset.sum_ite_eq', Finset.mem_univ, ite_eq_left_iff]\n                                        <;>\n                                        (try omega) <;>\n                                        (try simp_all [Fin.ext_iff]) <;>\n                                        (try aesop)\n                              exact h₁₀\n                        exact h₉\n              simp_all [h₇]\n            _ = ∑ j in Finset.univ, 1 := rfl\n            _ = ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), 1 := by\n              simp [Finset.sum_const]\n              <;>\n              simp_all [Finset.card_univ]\n              <;>\n              ring_nf\n              <;>\n              simp_all [Finset.card_univ]\n              <;>\n              aesop\n        _ = ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), 1 := by rfl\n    -- Derive a contradiction if n ≠ 0\n    have h₇ : 4 * n = 4 * n := by rfl\n    have h₈ : ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), (1 : ℕ) = 4 * n := by\n      simp [Finset.sum_const]\n      <;> simp [Finset.card_fin]\n      <;> ring\n    have h₉ : ∑ i : Fin n, (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) = 4 * n := by\n      exact h₅\n    have h₁₀ : ∑ i : Fin n, (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) = ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), 1 := by\n      exact h₆\n    have h₁₁ : ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), (1 : ℕ) = 4 * n := by\n      exact h₈\n    have h₁₂ : 4 * n = 0 := by\n      calc\n        4 * n = ∑ i : Fin n, (#{j : Fin (4 * n) | c j = i} : ℕ) := by rw [h₉]\n        _ = ∑ i : Fin (4 * n), 1 := by rw [h₁₀]\n        _ = 4 * n := by rw [h₈]\n        _ = 4 * n := by rfl\n        _ = 0 := by\n          -- Since n ≠ 0, this leads to a contradiction\n          have h₁₃ : n > 0 := Nat.pos_of_ne_zero hn'\n          have h₁₄ : 4 * n > 0 := by linarith\n          omega\n    have h₁₃ : n = 0 := by\n      omega\n    contradiction\n  -- If n = 0, then we can take S = ∅\n  subst h₁\n  use ∅\n  simp_all [Finset.sum_empty]\n  <;> aesop",
