      "= 2`, `4n = 8`. `Fin 8`, with `c : Fin 8 → Fin 2`. \n\nSuppose `c⁻¹(0) = {0,1,2,3}`, `c⁻¹(1) = {4,5,6,7}`. \nThen `S` should have 2 elements from each of these. \n\nPossible choice: `S = {0,1,4,5}`. \nSum: `1 + 2 + 5 + 6 = 14`. \nComplement sum: `3 + 4 + 7 + 8 = 22` ≠ 14. \nThis doesn't work. \n\nBut another choice `S = {0,3,4,7}`. \nSum: `1 + 4 + 5 + 8 = 18`. \nComplement sum: `2 + 3 + 6 + 7 = 18`. \n\nNow, `|S ∩ c⁻¹(0)| = 2`, `|S ∩ c⁻¹(1)| = 2`. \n\nThus, `S` works. \n\nHmm, so not every choice of 2 elements per color works, but some do. \n\nThus, we need a systematic way to choose 2 elements per color to make the sum condition satisfied. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can permute the elements to make the sum condition work. \n\nAlternatively, think about it differently: the sum of `(i + 1)` over all `i` is `2n(4n + 1)`, and we want `S` to have sum `n(4n + 1)`. \n\nThis is equivalent to `∑_{i ∈ S} i = n(4n + 1) - |S|`. But `|S| = 2n`, because we need `|S ∩ c⁻¹(i)| = 2` for each `i`, and there are `n` such `i`, so `|S| = 2n`.\n\nThus, `∑_{i ∈ S} i = n(4n + 1) - 2n = n(4n + 1 - 2) = n(4n - 1)`.",
      "we can do a recursive construction, but that seems hard.\n\nBut perhaps the sum condition is not that hard if we take a random subset of size `2n`? The expected sum of `(i + 1)` for a random subset of size `2n` is `(1/2) * ∑_{i} (i + 1) = n(4n + 1)`, which is exactly what we need. \n\nIn particular, if we choose deterministically a subset that averages out, we can try to take `S` to be the `2n` smallest or largest elements, but earlier calculations showed that this doesn't work. \n\nPerhaps we can arrange `S` to contain one element from each pair `{ (2k), (2k + 1) }`, but this is unclear. \n\nWait, here is an idea: pair up the elements as `(1, 4n), (2, 4n - 1), ..., (2n, 2n + 1)`. Then the sum of each pair is `4n + 1`. \n\nNow, if we take `S` to be `{1, 2, ..., 2n}`, then the sum is `n(2n + 1)`, and `Sᶜ` has sum `n(6n + 1)`, which is not equal. \n\nBut another approach: since `4n` is even, we can partition the set `Fin (4n)` into pairs of the form `(k, 4n - 1 - k)`, and then each pair sums to `(k + 1) + (4n - k) = 4n + 1`. \n\nIf we take `S` to contain exactly one element from each pair, then `S` will have size `2n`, and `∑_{i ∈ S} (i + 1) = (4n + 1) * 2n / 2 = n(4n + 1)`, because for each pair, exactly one element is in `S`.",
